4 (a) In this part the following words have the meanings indicated.
5 (b) “Aggrieved person” means any person that claims to have been injured by a
6 discriminatory housing practice.
7 (c) “Conciliation” means the attempted resolution of issues raised by a complaint,
8 or by the investigation of a complaint, through informal negotiations involving the
9 aggrieved person, the respondent, and the Commission.
10 (d) “Conciliation agreement” means a written agreement between the respondent
11 and the complainant setting forth the resolution of the issues in conciliation.
12 (e) “Discriminatory housing practice” means an act that is prohibited under §
13 20–705, § 20–706, § 20–707, or § 20–708 of this title.
14 (f) “Prevailing party” has the meaning as judicially determined under 42 U.S.C.
15 § 1988.
16 20–1035.
17 (a) In accordance with this section, an aggrieved person may commence a civil
18 action in an appropriate State court to obtain appropriate relief for an alleged
19 discriminatory housing practice or the breach of a conciliation agreement entered into
20 under this part.
21 (b) (1) The action shall be filed within 2 years after the later of the occurrence
22 or termination of the alleged discriminatory housing practice or the breach of the
23 conciliation agreement.
24 (2) (i) Except as provided in subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, the
25 computation of the 2–year period does not include any time during which an administrative
26 proceeding under this part was pending for a complaint or charge based on the alleged
27 discriminatory housing practice.
28 (ii) Subparagraph (i) of this paragraph does not apply to an action
29 arising from a breach of a conciliation agreement.
30 (3) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, an aggrieved person
31 may commence a civil action under this section:

