1 (i) not sooner than 130 days after a complaint has been filed under
2 § 20–1021 of this subtitle; and
3 (ii) regardless of the status of any complaint.
4 (c) (1) If the Commission or a State or local unit has obtained a conciliation
5 agreement with the consent of an aggrieved person, the aggrieved person may not file an
6 action under this section for the alleged discriminatory housing practice that forms the
7 basis for the complaint, except for the purpose of enforcing the terms of the conciliation
8 agreement.
9 (2) An aggrieved person may not commence a civil action under this section
10 with respect to an alleged discriminatory housing practice that forms the basis of a charge
11 issued by the Commission, if an administrative law judge has commenced a hearing on the
12 record under this part with respect to the charge.
13 (d) On application by a person alleging a discriminatory housing practice or a
14 person against whom a discriminatory housing practice is alleged, the court may:
15 (1) appoint an attorney for the person; or
16 (2) if, in the opinion of the court, the person is financially unable to bear
17 the costs of the action, authorize the commencement or continuation of a civil action under
18 subsection (a) of this section without the payment of fees, costs, or security.
19 (e) (1) In a civil action under this section, if the court finds that a
20 discriminatory housing practice has occurred, the court may:
21 (i) award to the plaintiff actual and punitive damages; and
22 (ii) subject to subsection (f) of this section, grant as relief, as the
23 court considers appropriate, any permanent or temporary injunction, temporary
24 restraining order, or other order, including an order enjoining the defendant from engaging
25 in the practice or ordering affirmative action.
26 (2) In a civil action under this section, the court may allow the prevailing
27 party reasonable attorney’s fees and costs.
28 (f) Relief granted under this section may not affect any contract, sale,
29 encumbrance, or lease consummated before the granting of relief and involving a bona fide
30 purchaser, encumbrancer, or tenant without actual notice of the filing of a complaint with
31 the Commission or civil action under this part.
32 (g) If the Commission certifies that the case is of general public importance and
33 on timely application, the Commission may:
34 (1) intervene in a civil action brought under this section; and

